; Regression test for issue #1794: price syntax / --revalued / --gains mysteries
; https://github.com/ledger/ledger/issues/1794
;
; The original report asked about the eight pricing syntaxes
;
;   @  @@      -- per-unit / total posting cost
;   {} {{}}   -- per-unit / total lot-price annotation
;   @= @@=    -- per-unit / total fixated posting cost
;   {=} {{=}} -- per-unit / total fixated lot-price annotation
;
; and several inconsistencies between them when used with --lots,
; --revalued, --revalued-only, --gain, and -V.  Most of the originally
; reported behavior either is intentional or has since been corrected;
; this test locks in the current, correct output so later changes cannot
; silently regress it.
;
; Concrete fix shipped with this test:
;   The `print` command now reconstructs the fixated marker `=` for @=
;   and @@= postings.  Previously `2 ETF @= 10 EUR` round-tripped back
;   out as `2 ETF @ EUR10`, silently demoting a fixated cost to an
;   ordinary one.
;
; Behaviors intentionally preserved (asserted below):
;   * every pricing syntax records a lot price on the annotated commodity;
;   * cost syntaxes (@, @@, @=, @@=) additionally record the posting date
;     as the acquisition date, while lot-annotation syntaxes ({}, {{}},
;     {=}, {{=}}) do not -- the user may supply `[date]` explicitly;
;   * the `=` fixated marker is displayed in --lots output for every
;     fixated syntax (issue #1196 originally restored it for {=}/{{=};
;     this test covers all four fixated forms);
;   * --revalued without -V does nothing when no market prices exist,
;     because a revaluation requires a changed market price;
;   * --revalued-only -V is empty when no price history is available --
;     there is nothing to revalue, so there are no <Revalued> postings.

P 2019-01-01 ETC  11 EUR
P 2019-02-01 ETC  12 EUR

2019-01-11
    (A)    2 ETF @ 10 EUR

2019-01-12
    (B)    2 ETF @@ 20 EUR

2019-01-13
    (C)    2 ETF {10 EUR}

2019-01-14
    (D)    2 ETF {{20 EUR}}

2019-01-15
    (F)    2 ETF @= 10 EUR

2019-01-16
    (G)    2 ETF @@= 20 EUR

2019-01-17
    (H)    2 ETF {=10 EUR}

2019-01-18
    (I)    2 ETF {{=20 EUR}}

2019-02-15
    (J)    2 ETF

; All eight syntaxes produce the same internal lot price (EUR10); the
; fixated forms additionally carry the `=` marker.  Cost syntaxes
; (A, B, F, G) record the posting date as the acquisition date.
test bal --flat --no-total --lots
2 ETF {EUR10} [2019/01/11]  A
2 ETF {EUR10} [2019/01/12]  B
       2 ETF {EUR10}  C
       2 ETF {EUR10}  D
2 ETF {=EUR10} [2019/01/15]  F
2 ETF {=EUR10} [2019/01/16]  G
      2 ETF {=EUR10}  H
      2 ETF {=EUR10}  I
               2 ETF  J
end test

; `print` reconstructs the source form of each posting.  The fixated
; cost marker `=` survives the round trip for @= (F) and @@= (G);
; before the fix they printed as bare `@` / `@@`.  {=} (H) and {{=}}
; (I) already round-tripped correctly.
test print
2019/01/11 <Unspecified payee>
    (A)                                        2 ETF @ EUR10

2019/01/12 <Unspecified payee>
    (B)                                        2 ETF @@ EUR20

2019/01/13 <Unspecified payee>
    (C)                                 2 ETF {EUR10}

2019/01/14 <Unspecified payee>
    (D)                                 2 ETF {EUR10}

2019/01/15 <Unspecified payee>
    (F)                                        2 ETF @= EUR10

2019/01/16 <Unspecified payee>
    (G)                                        2 ETF @@= EUR20

2019/01/17 <Unspecified payee>
    (H)                                 2 ETF {=EUR10}

2019/01/18 <Unspecified payee>
    (I)                                 2 ETF {=EUR10}

2019/02/15 <Unspecified payee>
    (J)                                        2 ETF
end test

; No market prices exist for ETF, so -V cannot revalue any posting.
; --revalued-only therefore emits no output; this is correct behavior,
; not a bug (see #1794, observation 3).
test reg --revalued-only -V
end test
